was hard to separate from the other big news of the time, the Republican Na=
tional Convention and the ugly final days of Biden=E2=80=99s moribund campa=
ign. Trump=E2=80=99s numbers came back down after Harris entered the fray a=
nd sucked up all the oxygen in the race. Around the time of the first assas=
sination attempt, Trump was averaging around 45 percent in horse-race polls=
=2E Today, two months later? Well, Trum=
p is averaging around 45 percent in ho=
rse-race polls.

The stability of the polls in the face of so many historic but also wacky e=
vents is obviously a reflection of the country=E2=80=99s deep partisanship.=
 Republicans are gonna
Republican, Democrats are gonna Democrat, and the diminishing pool of swing=
 voters will continue to show up in Pennsylvania focus groups with CNN=E2=
=80=99s Phil Mattingly. But the lack of volatility in the polling averages =
is also an expression of the electorate=E2=80=99s pessimism about politics =
generally, and skepticism about the 2024 nominees, specifically. Trump, as =
both president and former president, has never had an approval rating over =
50 percent, even after almost getting murdered on national television. In t=
wo elections, Trump has failed to earn more than 48 percent of the vote, an=
d he=E2=80=99s unlikely to do better this year.

Harris, meanwhile, has erased Biden=E2=80=99s prior deficits with demograph=
ic groups and inspired enough Democrats to give her a modest lead over Trum=
p. But large chunks of the electorate still say she=E2=80=99s either too li=
beral or that they don=E2=80=99t know enough about her. Yes, Harris has see=
n her arrow trend upward since July, but her lead over Trump
has mostly plateaued following the convention. She leads Trump by only 2.7 =
points in the FiveThirtyEight national average, within the margin of error,=
 and well within the polling error spreads of 2016 and 2020. Importantly, H=
arris is still lagging behind Biden=E2=80=99s 2020 numbers with certain gro=
ups she needs to shore up, including young, Black, and Latino voters.

All of this means=E2=80=94prepare to be bored!=E2=80=94that the race remain=
s very close and will be decided by the whims of a small number of people i=
n about seven states. It=E2=80=99s why you should, of course, pay attention=
 to the national polls as a reflection of the country=E2=80=99s mood, but p=
ay more attention to polling in the Electoral College battlegrounds that wi=
ll actually tip the race. And in each of those states, keep an especially w=
atchful eye on voting blocs that have shifted one way or another from the 2=
020 election and even the midterms of 2022, when Democrats solidified their=
 support with
college-educated white voters as a bulwark against Trumpism.

There are a few shifting dynamics I=E2=80=99ve been watching closely for cl=
ues about where this race is going. Every election is different, but with l=
ess than 50 days to go, a few early trends are becoming more durable, sugge=
sting that both Harris and Trump may be putting together coalitions that lo=
ok ever-so-slightly different from the ones that decided the previous elect=
ion. For instance, Trump is making inroads with Black and Hispanic men, to =
the point where Harris has yet to reach Biden=E2=80=99s 2020 support among =
voters of color. Meanwhile, Harris could make up for those losses with hist=
oric levels of support among female voters, thanks in part to the emergence=
 of abortion rights as a single-issue dealbreaker for women in the Dobbs er=
a. We=E2=80=99ll only know for sure come Election Day.

But there=E2=80=99s one demographic shift that no longer seems hypothetical=
=E2=80=94and that=E2=80=99s the movement of young
men over the last four years away from Democrats and toward Trump=E2=80=99s=
 Republican Party.

