          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The same is true re=
garding the news of the second Trump assassination attempt. Back in July, a=
fter a gunman fired on Trump in Pennsylvania, polls showed the former presi=
dent gaining around a point in the polls, but that bump was hard to separat=
e from the other big news of the time, the Republican National Convention a=
nd the ugly final days of Biden=E2=80=99s moribund campaign. Trump=E2=80=99=
s numbers came back down after Harris entered the fray and sucked up all th=
e oxygen in the race. Around the time of the first assassination attempt, T=
rump was averaging around 45 percent in horse-race polls. Today, two months=
 later? Well, Trump is averaging around 45 percent in horse-race polls.<br/=
><br/>The stability of the polls in the face of so many historic but also w=
acky events is obviously a reflection of the country=E2=80=99s deep partisa=
nship. Republicans are gonna
Republican, Democrats are gonna Democrat, and the diminishing pool of swing=
 voters will continue to show up in Pennsylvania focus groups with CNN=E2=
=80=99s <b>Phil Mattingly</b>. But the lack of volatility in the polling av=
erages is also an expression of the electorate=E2=80=99s pessimism about po=
litics generally, and skepticism about the 2024 nominees, specifically. Tru=
mp, as both president and former president, has never had an approval ratin=
g over 50 percent, even after almost getting murdered on national televisio=
n. In two elections, Trump has failed to earn more than 48 percent of the v=
ote, and he=E2=80=99s unlikely to do better this year. <br/><br/>Harris, me=
anwhile, has erased Biden=E2=80=99s prior deficits with demographic groups =
and inspired enough Democrats to give her a modest lead over Trump. But lar=
ge chunks of the electorate still say she=E2=80=99s either too liberal or t=
hat they don=E2=80=99t know enough about her. Yes, Harris has seen her arro=
w trend upward since July, but her lead over Trump
has mostly plateaued following the convention. She leads Trump by only 2.7 =
points in the FiveThirtyEight national average, within the margin of error,=
 and well within the polling error spreads of 2016 and 2020. Importantly, H=
arris is still lagging behind Biden=E2=80=99s 2020 numbers with certain gro=
ups she needs to shore up, including young, Black, and Latino voters.<br/><=
br/>All of this means=E2=80=94<i>prepare to be bored!</i>=E2=80=94that the =
race remains very close and will be decided by the whims of a small number =
of people in about seven states. It=E2=80=99s why you should, of course, pa=
y attention to the national polls as a reflection of the country=E2=80=99s =
mood, but pay <i>more</i> attention to polling in the Electoral College bat=
tlegrounds that will <i>actually</i> tip the race. And in each of those sta=
tes, keep an especially watchful eye on voting blocs that have shifted one =
way or another from the 2020 election and even the midterms of 2022, when D=
emocrats solidified their support with
college-educated white voters as a bulwark against Trumpism. <br/><br/>Ther=
e are a few shifting dynamics I=E2=80=99ve been watching closely for clues =
about where this race is going. Every election is different, but with less =
than 50 days to go, a few early trends are becoming more durable, suggestin=
g that both Harris and Trump may be putting together coalitions that look e=
ver-so-slightly <i>different</i> from the ones that decided the previous el=
ection. For instance, Trump is making inroads with Black and Hispanic men, =
to the point where Harris has yet to reach Biden=E2=80=99s 2020 support amo=
ng voters of color. Meanwhile, Harris could make up for those losses with h=
istoric levels of support among female voters, thanks in part to the emerge=
nce of abortion rights as a single-issue dealbreaker for women in the <i>Do=
bbs</i> era. We=E2=80=99ll only know for sure come Election Day.<br/><br/>B=
ut there=E2=80=99s one demographic shift that no longer seems hypothetical=
=E2=80=94and that=E2=80=99s the movement of young
men over the last four years away from Democrats and toward Trump=E2=80=99s=
 Republican Party.<br/></td>
