          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">You might have miss=
ed it, but at a rally in Las Vegas over the weekend, Trump welcomed a trio =
of young male internet stars=E2=80=94<b>Bryce Hall</b>, and <b>Kyle Forgear=
d</b>, and <b>Salim Sirur</b> of the Nelk Boys=E2=80=94to the stage and smi=
led as they took turns endorsing him. All three are full-spectrum content c=
reators=E2=80=94YouTubers, podcasters, TikTok stars=E2=80=94who are extreme=
ly popular on the internet with younger men who see Trump as a no-bullshit =
role model and Democrats as a bunch of politically correct weenies. Forgear=
d even used his moment at the mic to attack <b>Tim Walz</b> for passing a t=
ax in Minnesota on Zyn=E2=80=94the unofficial nicotine pouch of guys who ju=
st wanna have fun. =E2=80=9CHe put a 95 percent tax on Zyn! We gotta get th=
at removed, President Trump!=E2=80=9D Forgeard proclaimed, as the crowd boo=
ed Walz for his nanny state ways.<br/><br/>I=E2=80=99ve written a
lot about the pro-Trump drift of young male voters since the last election,=
 and so have others. There are many explanations for it: Trump=E2=80=99s ra=
scally appeal to dudes, society=E2=80=99s changing norms and expectations a=
round boyhood and masculinity, studies showing a rise in loneliness among y=
oung men, difficulty accessing the economy, a digital media environment rul=
ed by hypermasculine podcasters and video creators=E2=80=94and yes=E2=80=94=
the obvious lack of a truly <i>cool</i> male Democratic presidential nomine=
e since <b>Barack Obama</b>. <br/><br/>The movement of young men away from =
the Democratic Party is real=E2=80=94and probably unrecoverable before Elec=
tion Day. In 2020, Biden won both men and women under 30 by large, double-d=
igit margins. Overall, he won 60 percent of the youth vote=E2=80=94the winn=
ing margin Democrats have needed with young voters going back to the Obama =
years. Since then, though, Democrats have lost serious ground with young me=
n, creating a remarkable Gen Z gender gap. The
latest evidence: A new ABC News <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/e=
yJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dSX1pvYmlMTnRSV1BuWUV0ckhMcz0iLCJo=
cmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGFuZ2VycmVzZWFyY2guY29tL3dwLWNvbnRlbnQvdXBsb2Fkcy8=
xMjM2YTFBZnRlcnRoZUhhcnJpcy1UcnVtcERlYmF0ZS5wZGY_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPVRoZStCZX=
N0KyUyNitUaGUrQnJpZ2h0ZXN0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4OSUyRjE2JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwM=
jZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1UaGUrQmVzdCslMjYrVGhlK0JyaWdodGVzdCstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUy=
ODklMkYxMSUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZX=
JuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoxMDM1ODg5fQ/1a647253a3d9ce=
7081ad1e77f1a97bb389974ef94247655328ac870a71947b6c" style=3D"color:#d40000;=
text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">poll</a></u> this week=
end, showing Harris leading Trump by an astounding 38-point margin among wo=
men 18-29. But among men under 30? Harris only led Trump<i> by three points=
</i>. <br/><br/>The Democrats=E2=80=99 competitive advantage with young men=
, apparent in exit polls just four years ago, is now completely gone. The m=
ovement is driven by a lot of young white men, yes, but Trump=E2=80=99s sup=
port among young Black and young Latino men is higher than it was four year=
s ago, too. It=E2=80=99s hard to see how Harris erases that deficit in the =
next 49 days. Can anyone name a Democrat who can go into the media spaces w=
here Trump is popular=E2=80=94the Nelk Boys,
<b>Theo Von</b>, <b>Joe Rogan</b>=E2=80=94and make the case for Harris? <b>=
Bernie Sanders</b> has done several of them, but it hasn=E2=80=99t moved th=
e needle. Walz himself could appear on <i>New Heights</i> with the <b>Kelce=
</b> brothers or <i>Pardon My Take</i> to talk football, but I have a hunch=
 those guys don=E2=80=99t want to get involved in politics=E2=80=94even if =
<b>Travis Kelce</b>=E2=80=99s girlfriend has made her endorsement known. Bu=
t again, I don=E2=80=99t see how that changes the Gen Z bro vote in a meani=
ngful way at this point. Early voting has already kicked off in several sta=
tes. <br/><br/>Not every young man out there cares about crypto or Zyn or p=
ronoun culture in the same way the loudest voices in the manosphere do. But=
 it=E2=80=99s undeniable that a political shift has taken hold with Gen Z m=
en, and I have a hard time seeing how Democrats win that support back anyti=
me soon. The upside for Harris? Her support with young women is so strong t=
hat it offsets any losses with young men, who, past
experience shows, are less likely to vote than their female peers anyway.<b=
r/></td>
